useholds, even through the forcible conscription of native brides. In her comparative analysis of Dutch, English, French, Italian, Portuguese, and Spanish texts, Nocentelli shows how sexual behaviors and erotic desires quickly came to define the limits within which Europeans represented not only Asia but also themselves.Drawing on a wide range of European sources on polygamy, practices of male genital modification, and the allegedly excessive libido of native women, Empires of Love emphasizes the overlapping and mutually transformative construction of race and sexuality during Europe's early overseas expansion, arguing that the encounter with Asia contributed to the development of Western racial discourse while also shaping European ideals of marriage, erotic reciprocity, and monogamous affection.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aSex customszEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aSex customszEuropexHistoryy17th century. 0aSex customszSouth AsiaxHistoryy16th century. 0aSex customszSouth AsiaxHistoryy17th century. 4aCultural Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220777440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812207774423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812207774/original  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-04